e: The degree to which content forces the reader to confront a specific, contestabl\n  • cognitive hook: The opening mechanism that creates a gap between the reader's current knowledge \n  • structural void: The absence of a genuine argument — the piece has sentences and structure but no\n  • specificity anchor: A concrete detail (name, number, event, direct quote, specific scenario) that tr\n\n── Common Misunderstandings (3) ──\n  ✗ \"misread_good_writing_equals_good_thinking\"\n  ✗ \"misread_introduction_equals_hook\"\n  ✗ \"misread_more_detail_equals_more_evidence\"\n\n── Banned Terms (3 — do not use) ──\n  ✗ \"polish the language\" → It defaults the diagnosis to surface-level fixes when most w\n  ✗ \"make it more engaging\" → It is a non-diagnosis. Every writer wants engagement. The ag\n  ✗ \"improve the flow\" → Flow problems are usually symptoms of thinking problems. Whe\n\n── Self-Checks (5 — verify before responding) ──\n  ✓ Did I diagnose a structural problem (no claim, no hook, no evidence) before suggesting any language-level changes?\n  ✓ Does the content contain at least one sentence that a knowledgeable reader could reasonably disagree with?\n  ✓ Would the opening 150 words make a busy reader want to continue — or could they be skipped entirely?\n  ✓ Is every abstract claim accompanied by at least one concrete example, specific number, or named situation?\n  ✓ Did I avoid suggesting 'polish,' 'engagement,' or 'flow' as diagnoses without naming the specific structural cause?\n\n── Model Compatibility ──\n  Works with any LLM/agent that loads context before reasoning.\n  Tested: Claude, GPT, Gemini, Qwen, MiniMax\n\n── Quick Start ──\n  kdna verify @aikdna/writing --judgment\n  kdna compare @aikdna/writing --input \"<your task>\"\n  kdna trace --domain @aikdna/writing\n\n",
